{"title_page": "Plant blindness", "text_new": "'''Plant blindness''' is a form of [[cognitive bias]], which in its broadest meaning, is a human tendency to ignore [[plant]] species. This includes such phenomena as not noticing plants in the surrounding environment, not recognizing the importance of plant life to the whole [[biosphere]] and to human affairs, a philosophical view of plants as an inferior form of life to [[animal]]s and/or the inability to appreciate the unique features or aesthetics of plants.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Plant Blindness|journal=BioScience|volume=53|issue=10|pages=926|last=Allen|first=William|date=1 October 2003|publisher=[[American Institute of Biological Sciences]]|doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2003)053[0926:PB]2.0.CO;2}}</ref>\n\nThere have been made suggestions by scientists that the reason some people don't notice plants is because a majority of them are [[Sessility (motility)|stationary]] and similarly coloured, although other research has suggested that plant blindness is affected by cultural practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://psmag.com/news/can-plant-blindness-be-cured|title=Can Plant Blindness Be Cured?|last=Dasgupta|first=Shreya|date=27 September 2016|magazine=[[Pacific Standard]]}}</ref> A US study looked at how plants and animals are perceived using \"[[attentional blink]]\" (the ability to notice one of two rapidly presented images).<ref name=\"BBC\"/> This showed that participants more accurately detected images of animals than plants and suggested possible strategies for characterizing and overcoming [[zoocentrism]].<ref name=\"Attention Blinks\">{{cite journal | title=Attention \"Blinks\" Differently for Plants and Animals | author=Benjamin Balas and Jennifer L. Momsen | journal=[[CBE: Life Sciences Education]] | date=Fall 2014 | volume=13 | issue=3 | pages=437\u2013443 | doi=10.1187/cbe.14-05-0080 | pmid=25185227| pmc=4152205 }}</ref>{{clarify|reason=It is not clear how a difference in attentional blink provides strategies for overcoming zoocentrism|date=February 2020}}\n\nPotentially linked to [[nature deficit disorder]] and plant blindness, a limited interest in plants is resulting in fewer [[plant biology]] courses around the world and reduced public funding for [[plant science]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20190425-plant-blindness-what-we-lose-with-nature-deficit-disorder | title=Why 'plant blindness' matters \u2014 and what you can do about it | publisher=[[BBC]] |work=BBC Future| date=April 29, 2019 | accessdate=April 30, 2019 | author=[https://christinero.contently.com/ Christine Ro] of [[International Institute for Environment and Development]]}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term was coined in 1999 by botanists [[James Wandersee]] and [[Elisabeth Schussler]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Plant cognition]]\n* [[Plant rights]]\n* [[Speciesism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Plants and humans]]\n[[Category:Bioethics]]\n[[Category:Cognitive biases]]\n", "text_old": "'''Plant blindness''' is a form of [[cognitive bias]], which in its broadest meaning, is a human tendency to ignore [[plant]] species. This includes such phenomena as not noticing plants in the surrounding environment, not recognizing the importance of plant life to the whole [[biosphere]] and to human affairs, a philosophical view of plants as an inferior form of life to [[animal]]s and/or the inability to appreciate the unique features or aesthetics of plants.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Plant Blindness|journal=BioScience|volume=53|issue=10|pages=926|last=Allen|first=William|date=1 October 2003|publisher=[[American Institute of Biological Sciences]]|doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2003)053[0926:PB]2.0.CO;2}}</ref>\n\nThere have been made suggestions by scientists that the reason some people don't notice plants is because a majority of them are [[Sessility (motility)|stationary]] and similarly coloured, although other research has suggested that plant blindness is affected by cultural practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://psmag.com/news/can-plant-blindness-be-cured|title=Can Plant Blindness Be Cured?|last=Dasgupta|first=Shreya|date=27 September 2016|magazine=[[Pacific Standard]]}}</ref> A US study looked at how plants and animals are perceived using \"[[attentional blink]]\" (the ability to notice one of two rapidly presented images).<ref name=\"BBC\"/> This showed that participants more accurately detected images of animals than plants and suggested possible strategies for characterizing and overcoming [[zoocentrism]].<ref name=\"Attention Blinks\">{{cite journal | title=Attention \"Blinks\" Differently for Plants and Animals | author=Benjamin Balas and Jennifer L. Momsen | journal=[[CBE: Life Sciences Education]] | date=Fall 2014 | volume=13 | issue=3 | pages=437\u2013443 | doi=10.1187/cbe.14-05-0080 | pmid=25185227| pmc=4152205 }}</ref>{{clarify|reason=It is not clear how a difference in attentional blink provides strategies for overcoming zoocentrism|date=February 2020}}\n\nPotentially linked to [[nature deficit disorder]] and plant blindness, a limited interest in plants is resulting in fewer [[plant biology]] courses around the world and reduced public funding for [[plant science]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20190425-plant-blindness-what-we-lose-with-nature-deficit-disorder | title=Why 'plant blindness' matters \u2014 and what you can do about it | publisher=[[BBC]] |work=BBC Future| date=April 29, 2019 | accessdate=April 30, 2019 | author=[https://christinero.contently.com/ Christine Ro] of [[International Institute for Environment and Development]]}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term was coined in 1999 by botanists [[James Wandersee]] and [[Elisabeth Schussler]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Speciesism]]\n* [[Plant cognition]]\n* [[Plant rights]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Plants and humans]]\n[[Category:Bioethics]]\n[[Category:Cognitive biases]]\n", "name_